{"type":"message","id":"f5ad1c2c","parentId":"7f941ab5","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:38:40.562Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_b2gzg7khnfps_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 123815\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what concrete action to take.\r\n\r\nLooking at the goals:\r\n1. Phase 0 COMPLETE\r\n2. Phase 1 COMPLETE: Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n3. CFI Analysis is complete with findings documented in `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n4. Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe key pending task is the CFI-weighted compression experiment to compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline. This seems like the logical next step.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take:\r\n\r\n1. I could create a design document for the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n2. I could start implementing the experiment itself\r\n3. I could update the CFI_RESULTS.md with next steps\r\n\r\nGiven the architecture, I should design the experiment. Let me think about what this experiment would entail:\r\n\r\n- Current state: We have frequency-based invariants and their CFI scores\r\n- Baseline: Next-pulse prediction using frequency-based compression\r\n- Test: Next-pulse prediction using CFI-weighted compression (only high-CFI invariants)\r\n\r\nThe experiment would need to:\r\n1. Identify the next-pulse prediction task\r\n2. Compare using all invariants vs only high-CFI invariants\r\n3. Measure prediction accuracy\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action - I'll design the experiment specification that can guide implementation.\r\n\r\nActually, looking at the files mentioned, there's `research/CFI_RESULTS.md` that has the findings. The next step would be to design the actual experiment.\r\n\r\nLet me create a simple experiment design document that specifies:\r\n1. What we're comparing\r\n2. How we'll measure success\r\n3. The methodology\r\n\r\nThis is a concrete, advance-the-goals action.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 94.3% of invariants are low-CFI (metaprogramming noise), while only 5.7% are high-CFI (true causal anchors). This creates a natural experiment: does filtering by CFI improve next-pulse prediction compared to using all invariants?\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate an experiment specification for CFI-weighted compression that defines the baseline, test condition, and success metrics for the pending compression experiment.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nFiltering invariants by CFI score (retaining only high-CFI ≥0.7) will improve next-pulse prediction compared to frequency-weighted baseline because it removes metaprogramming noise.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline Condition\r\n- Use ALL invariants (N ≈ 17+ years of session data)\r\n- Weight = frequency count\r\n- Predict next-pulse content from frequency-weighted invariant pool\r\n\r\n### Test Condition  \r\n- Filter invariants to CFI ≥ 0.7 only (~5.7% of total)\r\n- Weight = CFI score (not frequency)\r\n- Predict next-pulse content from CFI-filtered invariant pool\r\n\r\n### Success Metric\r\n- Prediction accuracy: measured by overlap between predicted content and actual pulse content\r\n- Noise reduction: ratio of baseline pool size to filtered pool size\r\n\r\n## Implementation Notes\r\n- Invariant data location: `state/invariants/` (per-session) + `state/consolidated_invariants.json`\r\n- CFI scores stored in: `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n- Next-pulse prediction: simple cosine similarity between current session invariants and historical invariants\r\nfile: research/CFI_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:38:33\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774370320561}}
